{
  "text": "The cytochrome c oxidase subunit 2 (cox2) gene is the moststudied gene for the detection of Baylisascaris species and indeed appears to more specifically differentiate between this genus and other ascarids [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Two types of PCR assays targeting the cox2 gene of B. procyonis were able to detect single larvae and as few as 20 unembryonated eggs per gram of canine feces [CITATION_3] or as few as 25 eggs in soil and 5 eggs in water samples [CITATION_4] . Both assays were specific for Baylisascaris spp., and one of the two could separate B. procyonis and B. columnaris from B. transfuga [CITATION_5] ; however, it could not discriminate between B. procyonis and B. columnaris, because the cox2 sequences of these two species differ by only two bases [CITATION_6] . Other examples of cross-reactivity within the ascarid group have also been observed at the molecular level, especially in cases in which certain mitochondrial markers were compared [CITATION_7] or very closely related species like B. procyonis and B. columnaris were examined [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . However, because of several polymorphisms in both mitochondrial and nuclear markers of B. columnaris, it was hypothesized that these could potentially be used to differentiate between these two species in molecular diagnostic assays, including by PCR [CITATION_10] . This information is relevant to epidemiological investigations and to the development of control measures and yet is not as important for clinical management of cases, since the treatments for the two infections are similar (1).",
